metadata.name: Dialect #50
metadata.description:
Dialect is an exploration of text in graphical form. The collection began with a specific constraint: a string of characters would be the main input. This simple constraint triggered a journey into form, colour and minimalism. There is also a deep sense of nostalgia in some of the outputs. Colours intentionally fade into each other and sometimes fade away almost entirely, like an old polaroid photograph. Dialect can be defined as a particular form of a language which is peculiar to a specific region or social group. Similarly it is my hope that there are particular outputs in this collection that speak meaningfully to the individuals who own them.

Controls (in live view):
- Press [s] to save a high-resolution version of the image

Made in p5js
Created February 2023
By John Ryan

metadata.name: Dialect: Bold #139
metadata.description:
Dialect: Bold is the wild younger sibling of Dialect. As both Dialect collections are created using a string of text as the main input, "Bold" is also a play on the term used to denote the weight of a font. Many aesthetic decisions were made along the way to completing Dialect. Dialect: Bold is what would have happened had a different path been taken. Complimentary but different. Bold!

Controls (in live view):
- Press [s] to save a high-resolution version of the image

Made in p5js
Created March 2023
By John Ryan

metadata.name: Obliques #175
metadata.description:
Obliques are a reinterpretation of Parallels, a collection of AI generated color fields by Marc Maurer. Many of the pieces in that collection are CC0, which basically means they can be reused for other projects, like this one.

Obliques takes artifacts from Parallels and uses them as brushes, painting slices of the original image on the canvas in a (hopefully) pleasant, chaotic way.

About 10% will be "Glitched".

The "Source Material" property will tell you the name of piece that it is using.

You can see Marc Maurer's Parallels project here:
https://objkt.com/collection/KT1TiSEcASGD19SW8bmqrqgSgCBkwXqDdTJ1

Obliques are also CC0, so feel free use anything here in other projects.

You can read more about CC0 here:
https://creativecommons.org/share-your-work/public-domain/cc0/

G : Toggle Grain
M : Toggle Matte
S : Save Image
1 -> 6 : Set pixel density
(Default pixel density is 1 @ 2000x2000)

metadata.name: Leaf study #40
metadata.description:
This piece is an exploration of the mathematical rules that dictate plant growth as well as their photosynthesis. 

Features : 
- 22 color palettes 
- 3 types of leaf  : oak, reniform, thistle
- 2 cell states : filled, hollow
- 2 color modes : light, dark

Controls
- Press S : export the piece 
- Press 1 - 9 : change the pixel density ( to increase the size of the export ). the default value is 2. Beware hight resolution will slow down the piece
